arch:property.oc:show_val: This is a medium-size unit with relatively large pieces; much less fragmented than floor units, etc., inside B. 3. More sheep-size, but quite a bit of large mammal. Taxa include cattle, equid, pig, red deer, sheep. All body parts are represented, but long bones not so common and feet are rather sparse, especially since many of the phalanges are digested and hence entered the unit in dog poop. Ribs and vertebrae are somewhat more abundant than usual at Catal. Wild animals are adults, while sheep/goat cover a range of ages. There is quite a lot of digestion, showing that dog poop is present in substantial quantities. Burning is low, ca. 5%, and mostly low temperature. The surface condition is not very fresh (perhaps because we are relatively near the surface), but there are few signs of weathering through surface exposure, and most of the bone does not look rolled or trampled (edges of breaks are sharp). There are a few cut marks and an expedient bone point, and one large (ca. stork) sternum. There are several pathological bones that may come from one large animal. If they are all the same, it is cattle, but the only identifiable piece shows a rather different pattern of pathology. Two have cut marks, so the disease did not prevent them from eating it. There is little gnawing; it looks as though these were protected from dogs, but dog poop was collected and dumped here. The overall impression is of an accumulation of the remains of many daily meals (rather low coherence), rapidly buried and not worked over by dogs or trampled or redeposited by people. That is, midden-like material. Sample 2 (flot 5056) >4mm flotation 100% sorted, only diagnostics recorded and rest as flot frags. Medium-size sample, containing entirely macromammal fragments. Fish and microfauna are notably absent from this unit, and rare in the 1 and 2 mm flot as well (which do contain some bits of probably intrusive small rodent). Looks like the unit in general, with high digestion, etc., but includes some dog. Last number = 274
